<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-01-16T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-01-16T04:00:00-05:00" n="972" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d972">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51 Contractual Obligations/22:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-01-16T17:00:00+08:00">January 16, 1931—5
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received January 16—9:10 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>27. Department’s 3, January 3, 6 p.m. I have transmitted through the
                            Foreign Office a letter addressed to Dr. Wang Chung-hui, Chairman of the
                            Commission for the Reorganization of China’s Domestic and Foreign Loans,
                            stating the Department’s attitude as outlined in paragraph 4 of the
                            above-cited telegram.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
